arXiv:1707.03265v4 Announce Type: replace 
Abstract: In this paper, we prove the twin prime conjecture showing that  egin{align} \sum \limits_{\substack{p\leq x\p,p+2\in \mathbb{P}}}1\geq (1+o(1)) rac{x}{2\mathcal{C}\log^2 x}
onumber \end{align} where $\mathcal{C}:=\mathcal{C}(2)>0$ fixed and $\mathbb{P}$ is the set of all prime numbers. In particular, it implies  egin{align}
  \sum \limits_{p,p+2\in \mathbb{P}}1=\infty
onumber \end{align} when we take $x\longrightarrow \infty$ on both sides of the inequality. We start by developing a general method for estimating correlations of the form  egin{align} \sum \limits_{n\leq x}G(n)G(n+l)
onumber \end{align} for a fixed $1\leq l\leq x$ and where $G:\mathbb{N}\longrightarrow \mathbb{R}^{+}$.
